# Conventional Branch naming

This project follows **[Conventional Branch](https://conventional-branch.github.io/)** for branch names so purpose and automation stay clear.

## Shape

```
<type>/<description>
```

## Allowed `<type>` prefixes (common)

| Prefix     | Use                                  |
| ---------- | ------------------------------------ |
| `feature/` | New work (tasks, features)           |
| `fix/`     | Bug fixes                            |
| `hotfix/`  | Urgent production fixes              |
| `release/` | Release prep (e.g. `release/v1.2.0`) |

## Rules

1. **Lowercase** letters (`a-z`), **numbers** (`0-9`), **hyphens** (`-`) only in the description. **Dots** (`.`) are allowed in release-style names (e.g. `release/v1.2.0`).
2. **No** consecutive, leading, or trailing hyphens or dots (e.g. not `feature/foo--bar`, not `feature/-x`).
3. **No** spaces, underscores, or arbitrary special characters in the description.
4. **Include the issue number** when the branch implements a GitHub task/issue (e.g. `feature/9-ide-versions`, `feature/issue-9-ide-versions`).

## Task branches (this repo)

When starting work on a **task** (labeled `tasks` on GitHub), prefer:

```text
feature/<issue-number>-<short-slug>
```

Examples: `feature/9-ide-versions`, `feature/13-documentation`

Derive `<short-slug>` from the task title: lowercase, replace spaces with hyphens, strip bracket prefixes like `[Task 0.2]`, collapse multiple hyphens, keep it short (roughly 3–6 words max).

